'''Ron James''' (born April 28, 1964) is an [[arena football]] coach who is currently the head coach of the [[Atlantic City Blackjacks]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Siena College]]. He has been a football coach since 1986. Before becoming the Blackjacks' head coach for their inaugural 2019 season, James coached for the [[Las Vegas Gladiators]] from 2005 to 2006, the [[Utah Blaze]] from 2009 to 2013, the [[Pittsburgh Power]] in 2014, the [[Portland Steel]] in 2016, and the [[Tampa Bay Storm]] in 2017.

James grew up in [[Albany, New York]], where he played football at [[Christian Brothers Academy (Albany, New York)|Christian Brothers Academy]]. He then enrolled at Siena College, and played offensive line on the [[Siena Saints football]] team from 1982 to 1985.

==College career==
James accepted a scholarship offer from [[Siena College]], where he was an [[All-American]] offensive lineman.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/sports/54218911-77/james-team-blaze-says.html.csp |title=AFL: In all ways, Ron James leads Utah Blaze |author=Kyle Goon |date=June 1, 2012 |publisher=The Salt Lake Tribune |work=www.sltrib.com |accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref>

==Coaching career==
After multiple stops coaching in the [[NCAA]] and assistant jobs in the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL), James was named the head coach of the [[Las Vegas Gladiators]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3078586 |title=Gladiators name Ron James new head coach |date=August 24, 2004 |publisher=OurSports Central |work=www.oursportscentral.com |accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref> After a he compiled a 12–18 record, James was let go and joined the [[Utah Blaze]] staff. After [[Danny White]] resigned in 2008, James was promoted to head coach of the Blaze.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ksl.com/?nid=570&sid=3723138 |title=Ron James Named New Head Coach Of Utah Blaze |date=July 9, 2008 |publisher=KSL.com |work=www.ksl.com |accessdate=April 25, 2014}}</ref> The Blaze folded following the 2013 season and James was hired after week one of the 2014 season by the [[Pittsburgh Power]] when they fired head coach [[Derek Stingley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2010115-arena-football-league-timing-is-everything-for-pittsburgh-power-and-ron-james#articles/2010115-arena-football-league-timing-is-everything-for-pittsburgh-power-and-ron-james |title=Arena Football League: Timing Is Everything for Pittsburgh Power and Ron James |author=Matt Popchock |date=March 29, 2014 |publisher=Bleacher Report, Inc. |work=www.bleacherreport.com |accessdate=April 25, 2014}}James led the Power to a 15-3 record.</ref> The Power folded at the end of the season.

On January 30, 2016, James was hired as the new head coach and general manager of the team that became the [[Portland Steel]], replacing [[Andy Olson (American football)|Andy Olson]]. The Steel folded after the 2016 season.

On October 25, 2016, he was named the head coach of the [[Tampa Bay Storm]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.arenafan.com/news/?page=pressrel&article=13430 | title=Storm Names Ron James Head Coach | publisher=arenafan.com | date=October 25, 2016 | accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> He helped the Storm to a 10–4 regular season record and a berth in [[ArenaBowl XXX]], where they lost to the [[Philadelphia Soul]] by a score of 44–40.<ref name="coty"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.arenafootball.com/articles/soul-snare-second-straight-foster-trophy-in-arenabowl-xxx | title=Soul Snare Second Straight Foster Trophy in ArenaBowl XXX | publisher=arenafootball.com | accessdate=August 27, 2017 | deadurl=bot: unknown | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827235503/http://www.arenafootball.com/articles/soul-snare-second-straight-foster-trophy-in-arenabowl-xxx | archivedate=August 27, 2017 | df= }}</ref> The Storm, who finished with a 2–14 record in 2016, became the first team in AFL history to have a winning percentage of less than .200 in a season and then earn an ArenaBowl berth the next season. James was named the [[Marcum-Moss Head Coach of the Year|AFL Coach of the Year]] in 2017.<ref name="coty">{{cite web | url=http://www.arenafootball.com/articles/tampa-bays-james-named-marcum-moss-head-coach-of-the-year | title=Tampa Bay's James Named Marcum-Moss Head Coach of the Year | publisher=arenafootball.com | date=August 25, 2017 | accessdate=August 26, 2017 | deadurl=bot: unknown | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826204744/http://www.arenafootball.com/articles/tampa-bays-james-named-marcum-moss-head-coach-of-the-year | archivedate=August 26, 2017 | df= }}</ref> The Storm folded in December 2017. 

In 2018, James was hired as a senior analyst for the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]] of the [[Canadian Football League]]. He returned the AFL in 2019 as the inaugural head coach of the expansion [[Atlantic City Blackjacks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/atlantic-city-afl-team-announces-head-coach-coaching-staff/n-5443311 |title=Atlantic City AFL Team Announces Head Coach, Coaching Staff |website=OurSportsCentral.com |date=January 31, 2019}}</ref>

